SIMPLE: arrange
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Arrange
<hw>Ar*range"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Arranged</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Arranging</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>arayngen</ets>, OF. <ets>arengier</ets>, F. <ets>arranger</ets>,
fr. <ets>a</ets> (L. <ets>ad</ets>) + OF. <ets>rengier</ets>,
<ets>rangier</ets>, F. <ets>ranger</ets>. See <er>Range</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put in proper order; to dispose
(persons, or parts) in the manner intended, or best suited for the
purpose; <as>as, troops <ex>arranged</ex> for battle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So [they] came to the market place, and there he
<qex>arranged</qex> his men in the streets.</q>
<rj><qau>Berners.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] were beginning to <qex>arrange</qex> their hampers.</q>
<rj><qau>Boswell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A mechanism previously <qex>arranged</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Paley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To adjust or settle; to prepare; to determine;
<as>as, to <ex>arrange</ex> the preliminaries of an
undertaking</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Adjust; adapt; range; dispose;
classify.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>arranged</ent>⟦br⟧
